folder: Mulberry Street & Bayard Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Mulberry Street, east side, north from and including Bayard Street. Note P.S. No. 23, on the N.E. corner. Pushcart peddlers, vendors etc., are shown in this series of views, are still typical of this neighborhood ("Little Italy" or "Mulberry Bend").

About 1907.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

The same view, further southward.

About 1907.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

A portion of the foreground of No. 2. Note the 1-story frame structure adjoining No. 66 Mulberry Street the S.E. corner building. Shown on the right, is the humble start of a local bank; Banco De Prisco, which is now (1936), known as the Prisco Bank, and is located at No. 73, west side, north of Bayard Street;

About 1907.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: 98-100 Bayard Street, Manhattan, N.Y.
text:
(1)
Feast of San Rocco (St. Roch), 1932, No. 7. Paraders, a group of children and others, at 98-100 Bayard Street near the corner of Baxter Street.

August 16, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
No. 8. A larger view of the same scene, showing an elaborate candelabrum borne by four young women. This view shows the end of western end of Bayard Street, at Baxter Street.

August 16, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)
No. 9. A group of children who have been in the procession. Notice the number of angels.

August 16, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.
title: Feast of San Rocco [Saint Roch].
